{{unreferenced|date=April 2012}} {{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Cabaret_Scene.jpg | backcolor=#FBF5DF | painting_alignment=right | image_size=300px | title=Cabaret Scene | artist=[[Salvador Dalí]] | year=1922 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric=52 | width_metric=41 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Paris]] | museum=[[private collection]] of Francois Petit }} '''''Cabaret Scene''''' (1922) is a painting by the [[Spain|Spanish]] [[Surrealism|surrealist]] [[Salvador Dalí]]. It was a unique [[Cubism|cubist]] experiment that came between Dalí's early [[Impressionism|impressionist]] work and the classic [[Surrealism|surrealist]] technique he would later develop. Dalí was inspired by [[Pablo Picasso]] after he got expelled from the School of Fine Arts in Spain. His inspiration was shown in his paintings, such as this one.
