{{Orphan|date=July 2016}}
The '''Egyptian pavilion''' is a national pavilion of the Venice Biennale. It houses Egypt's official representation during the Biennale. The building is part of a complex that [[Brenno Del Giudice]] designed in 1932 to house Venetian decorative arts on [[Sant'Elena]] Island—an expansion of the Biennale from its main Giardini area. The building later served as Switzerland's national pavilion before the country moved to a new pavilion in 1952 and left the building to Egypt. The national pavilions for Serbia and Venice flank the Egyptian pavilion. Egypt's 1995 exhibition won the Biennale's Golden Lion award for best national pavilion.

== Building ==

In 1932, Italian architect [[Brenno Del Giudice]] designed a series of buildings on [[Sant'Elena]] as an expansion from the main [[Giardini]] area of the [[Venice Biennale]]. The island of Sant'Elena is separated from the Giardini by a bridged canal.{{sfn|Re Rebaudengo|2013|p=174}} The original complex was designed as a single unit to exhibit Venetian [[decorative arts]].{{sfn|Re Rebaudengo|2013|p=177}} Its façade repeats a pattern of straight and curved features,{{sfn|Re Rebaudengo|2013|p=177}} including multiple arches in its façade's recesses and openings.{{sfn|Re Rebaudengo|2013|p=174}} The complex was later split into two national pavilions flanking a central Venetian pavilion{{sfn|Re Rebaudengo|2013|p=177}} of which Switzerland received the national pavilion on the left.{{sfn|Re Rebaudengo|2013|p=175}} When Switzerland moved to a new pavilion in 1952,{{sfn|Re Rebaudengo|2013|p=183}} Egypt moved into the Del Giudice building, where it remains as of 2013.{{sfn|Re Rebaudengo|2013|p=175}} The space consists of a rectangular room with two smaller rooms adjacent. The building's entrance extends outwards from its façade, similar to the visual style of the Venetian pavilion next door.{{sfn|Re Rebaudengo|2013|p=175}} The letters "RAE" are carved into the façade above the entrance archway, for "Repubblica Araba d'Egitto".{{sfn|Stock|2015}}

Del Giudice expanded the complex in 1938 to add pavilions on each side of the main structure.{{sfn|Re Rebaudengo|2013|p=176}} Sweden used the building to the left of the Egyptian pavilion,{{sfn|Re Rebaudengo|2013|p=176}} but the Nordic countries constructed their own pavilion between 1958 and 1962,{{sfn|Re Rebaudengo|2013|p=190}} and Serbia received Sweden's old pavilion.{{sfn|Re Rebaudengo|2013|p=176}} The Egyptian pavilion rests between the Serbian and Venetian pavilions.{{sfn|Re Rebaudengo|2013|pp=162–3}}

