{{short description|Australian philosopher}} {{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Western philosophy]] |era = [[Contemporary philosophy|21st-century philosophy]] |color = |image = |name = '''Robert Sinnerbrink''' |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |school_tradition = [[Continental philosophy|Continental]] | institutions = [[Macquarie University]] |main_interests = [[philosophy of film]], [[Heidegger]] | thesis_title = Metaphysics of modernity: The problem of identity and difference in Hegel and Heidegger | thesis_url = https://ses.library.usyd.edu.au/handle/2123/5710 | thesis_year = 2001 | doctoral_advisor = [[György Márkus]] | doctoral_students = |notable_ideas = | spouse = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of Sydney]] |influences = [[Hegel]], [[Heidegger]] |influenced = |awards = [[ARC Future Fellowship]], [[University Medal in Philosophy]] (USYD) }}
'''Robert Sinnerbrink''' is an Australian philosopher and Associate Professor of [[Philosophy]] at [[Macquarie University]]. He is an [[ARC Future Fellowship]] recipient<ref>{{cite web |title=Robert Sinnerbrink |url=https://researchers.mq.edu.au/en/persons/robert-sinnerbrink |website=Macquarie University |accessdate=14 October 2018 |language=en}}</ref> and a former Chair of the [[Australasian Society for Continental Philosophy]] (2007-2010).<ref>{{cite web |title=History of the ASCP |url=https://www.ascp.org.au/about-the-ascp/history-of-the-ascp |website=Australasian Society for Continental Philosophy |accessdate=14 October 2018 |language=en-gb}}</ref> Sinnerbrink is known for his research on [[aesthetics]] and [[philosophy of film]].
==Books== * ''Cinematic Ethics: Exploring Ethical Experience through Film'', Abingdon and New York: Routledge, 2016 * ''New Philosophies of Film: Thinking Images'', New York/London: Continuum, 2011 * ''Understanding Hegelianism'', Chesham: Acumen Press, 2007 * ''Critique Today'', edited with Jean-Philippe Deranty, [[Nicholas H. Smith]], and Peter Schmiedgen, Leiden: Brill, 2006 * ''Recognition, Work, Politics: New Directions in French Critical Theory'', edited with Jean-Philippe Deranty, Danielle Petherbridge, and John Rundell, Leiden: Brill, 2007
