{{Distinguish|Winifred Smith}} {{Infobox person | name = Winifred Lily Boys-Smith | image = Winifred_Boys-Smith.gif | alt = | caption = Photo of Winifred Boys-Smith from the Otago Witness in March 1911 | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{Birth date|1865|11|7}} | birth_place = [[Corsham]], [[Wiltshire]], [[England]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1939|1|1|1865|11|7}} | death_place = | nationality = | other_names = | occupation = Scientist, Professor | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }} '''Winifred Lily Boys-Smith''' (7 November 1865&ndash;1 January 1939) was an English-born New Zealand science artist and lecturer, university professor, school principal. She was born in [[Corsham]], [[Wiltshire]], [[England]] on 7 November 1865.<ref name="DNZB Boys-Smith">{{DNZB|title=Winifred Lily Boys-Smith|first= Heath|last= McDonald|id=3b41|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref>
Boys-Smith studied at the [[University of Cambridge]] between 1891 and 1895. She took the full honours course for [[Natural Sciences (Cambridge)|natural sciences tripos]], however, was only given a certificate as women were not granted degrees at the time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://teara.govt.nz/en/biographies/3b41/boys-smith-winifred-lily|title=Boys-Smith, Winifred Lily|last=Taonga|first=New Zealand Ministry for Culture and Heritage Te Manatu|access-date=2018-10-09|language=en}}</ref>
She taught at [[Cheltenham Ladies College]].<ref name="DNZB Boys-Smith" />
Her nephew, John Sandwith Boys Smith, was Master of St John's College, Cambridge <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.joh.cam.ac.uk/correspondence-and-papers-john-sandwith-boys-smith-1901-1991-theologian-master-st-johns-1959-1969|title=Correspondence and papers of John Sandwith Boys Smith (1901-1991), theologian, Master of St John's 1959-1969 {{!}} St John's College, Cambridge|website=www.joh.cam.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2017-01-20}}</ref> and Vice-Chancellor of the University of Cambridge from 1963 to 1965.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.v-c.admin.cam.ac.uk/role-vice-chancellor/history-vice-chancellorship|title=History of the Vice-Chancellorship|last=Weglowska|first=Magdalena|date=2015-02-23|website=www.v-c.admin.cam.ac.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-01-20}}</ref>
